
South Africa's Truth and Reconciliation Commission was established to clear the air
after the ugly apartheid struggle. Retired Archbishop Tutu headed the Commission. It
worked two plus years, holding countrywide meetings. It was controversial from the start.
Commission leaks prompted de Klerk, the last white President, to threaten a court challenge

The final 3,500-page report was issued on 29 October 1998. The white majority received the
greater blame for rights violations, but the black ANC was also cited. De Klerk's name did
not appear in the report. Botha, the Inkatha Party, the ruling ANC, and Winnie Mandela were
specifically cited.
